segments.text: Dr. F. P. Jaggi.
Today's date is January 24th, 1980, and this is Terry Anderson.
Today's interview is with Dr. Frederick P. Jaggi, Jr., retired professor of Veterinary Medicine.
Today's date is January 24th, 1980.
Now, you were born on May 5th of 1900 in Mexico, and you attended
high school in San Antonio.
Could you tell us about your experiences in high school?
Well, I didn't have any particular experiences in high school that were different from most of the other boys in high school.
Oh, we participated in sports of one kind and another, and then the usual academic courses that everybody took,
But beyond that, I had no particular activities.
In other words, lots of the boys went in for debating societies and all that.
I did not have time for that because I worked after school.
What kind of work did you do?
Delivering shoes for a shoe company there.
You were born in Mexico.
That's right.
How'd you get up to San Antonio, and could you tell us about your parents' background?
Well, how far back you want to go?
Well, go ahead, go ahead.
My mother and father were from Eagle Pass originally, and then my father went to Mexico working for mining companies, and then
I was born in Pachuca, Mexico, the state of Hidalgo.
And my father was, well, they called him a mining engineer.
Pachuca was, at that time, was the biggest silver mining center in the world, I guess.
And I was born there.
We left there and went to Mexico City.
Let me just say you were wondering about my education.
I started out with a governess.
There was four of us children, and we had a governess then for one year.
After that, I went to the Methodist Mission School there in Pachuca.
And when the Madero Revolution took over,
the town in 1911.
We moved to Mexico City and I went to the American school there.
And we stayed there till, well, the end of the summer of 1912 when we moved to San Antonio.
Then I went through the San Antonio schools.
Now did your father have an engineering degree?
No.
Could you tell me about his education?
No, I can't.
All I know is
Well he went to St. Mary's School in San Antonio, I know that, or University or whatever it was, which is still there, and beyond that I can't tell you anything about his education.
Did he work for a company or did he work for the Mexican government?
Yes, he worked for a company.
Now you were down in Mexico at a rather turbulent time.
Do you, I know you're only 11 or 12 years old at this time, but do you remember anything, any episodes during the Mexican Revolution?

Well, I remember when the, when the Madarizas took over the town of Pachuca, they came in and shot it up and burnt some of the buildings and the, I guess you'd call it the National Guard or Army, whatever it was,
It's a little different from our system in that each state more or less operated independently.
At any rate, there was a barracks there with soldiers, and they just took out.
They left.
And after two or three days while the Maderistas established
Oh, some sort of semblance of order there.
They executed a man which I visited, which I viewed.
I shouldn't say visited, I viewed it.
I'm glad I didn't visit it.
They shot him?
Yes, they shot him.
He was a bureaucrat on the other side?
Well, no, they got him for, oh, you might call it vandalizing or looting.

because all the workmen, the peons and all those, when the maderistas started into town, they just became a mob and did a lot of looting, and they're the ones who burned the buildings that were burned and that sort of thing.
The governor, of course, took out
because this was a different regime, and they finally straightened things out.
It didn't last too long, that is the disorder, and then it went on from there, and we went to Mexico City, and Madero was president then.
Diaz had been.
He overthrew
Madero overthrew Diaz, and then he became president and was in Mexico City during the time that we were living there, and beyond that I can't tell you anything about there.
This is a time of rather intense nationalism for the Mexicans.
Was there any anti-Americanism that you can remember at that time?
Oh yes, there was some.
There's always been antagonism to Americans.
Americans have the peculiar habit of not understanding foreigners.
They think they should all behave and act like Americans, and well, the Americans seem to feel like they're a little superior.
So there's always a resentment there.
And yes, there were some anti-American demonstrations
Not bad, but your family?
No, no, our family was not, no.
Okay, let's move north then, back up to San Antonio.
What were the subjects that you liked the most when you were in high school?
I didn't particularly care too much for any of the subjects.
I guess mechanical drawing and shop work, things of that nature were my
principal interests.
I never was a whiz at mathematics or ancient history or any of that stuff.
I shouldn't call it stuff, but those courses, and well I did like I think probably botany.
We didn't have zoology, but we did have botany and we had an excellent
teacher, and I liked that.
It was very interesting.
How large was the school?
How many students?
Oh, there was only one high school in San Antonio at that time.
That was Old Main Avenue High School, and I imagine there was about 2,000 in the high school.
I understand they must have
seven or eight high schools there now.
Yeah, yeah.
Now a rather interesting world event was exploding at this time.
World War I, 1914, erupts in Europe, and then we joined the war in 1917, and you're 17 years old at that time.
Do you remember what it was, if the war itself had much of an impact on high school, or right after you got out of high school?
Not so much impact on high school,
It did.
The people, of course, reacted to it.
And then in the summer, I guess it was, of 1918, three of us went up to work in the wheat harvest, which was popular at that time.
They were short of hands, and we went up through Kansas and South Dakota working in the wheat harvest.
On the way back, I had, I guess I was 18 then, and I registered for the draft in Amarillo on the way home.
But beyond that, it did not affect us a whole lot.
We had lots of soldiers there in San Antonio, and Fort Sam Houston, Camp Trev, Kelly Field, and all that, and
Oh, we played a lot of them football.
We didn't get very far with them, but nevertheless we did play them, and some of their people from time to time coached us.
That is the high school team.
Pretty good relations between the high school kids and the servicemen?
Oh yes, yes.
Good, good relations as far as I can
far as I was concerned, we had good relations, and I don't remember any disagreeableness between any of the students and any of the service people.
Southern Texas is heavily influenced by German immigration a century ago, and I was, I'm sure that one of the languages in high school
was German at this time, and in many high schools across the country during World War I they banned the instruction of German language.
Do you remember if they did that at San Antonio?
We didn't have German in the high school.
We had Spanish.
Spanish and Latin.
And in the grade schools before the war they had, in some of the schools they had German, and in some of them they had Spanish.
But
They didn't have German in high school.
Now why exactly did you go up to the Midwest to help with the grain harvest?
Well, I had to do something for the summer.
It seemed adventuresome, and we got us an old Model T Ford
three of us, and we and we took off.
We got 50 cents an hour working in- Fifty cents an hour?
Yeah, big money.
That is pretty good.
So working in the harvest and we'd stay in one place until that was harvested out and then we'd move on north to places that were just starting up and
Oh, we did too much exploring, I guess, to make much money.
We wanted to see this and that and the Black Hills and Montana, Wyoming.
So we spent most of our money just traveling around, looking at things, and then we'd run out of money and then we'd go back to work somewhere.
50 cents an hour seems pretty good for 1917, considering that it wasn't until 1937 when we get the first minimum wage, and that's only 25 cents an hour.
Well, this was set by the government.
Really?
And in order to get workers, I think at first it was 45 cents, and then they went to 50 cents an hour.
And, of course, you've got your room and board.
Yeah.
on these farms.
The rooms were usually questionable, but the food was all right.
Lots of it.
We usually slept right on the ground in our own blankets rather than go into those places where all the granaries and places that stick you to sleep.
Were you drafted during the war?
No, the war ended before I got out of high school.
Oh, I thought you graduated in the summer of 1918.
Did you?
No.
From high school?
No, in January of 1919.
Oh, okay, then the war just ended.
Okay.
But you registered during the summer of 1918 and you did register?
Yeah, in Amarillo on the way home.
And then that winter I graduated from high school.
Oh, okay.
I thought you probably graduated in June.
No.
No, I didn't graduate in June.
Why not?
Well, my education had lots of ups and downs.
See, I was in the school in Pachuca when the Motheristas took the place over.
And that was along in May, I guess it was.
And they closed the school down, so there's no grades.
Then I went to Mexico City, and they stuck me in the grade there, fourth grade, I guess it was.
And it was a tough school.
It was right up there.
Then we came to San Antonio, and the grades were divided.
And they put me in the high fifth, I think it was.
So that was in September.
So I didn't start with the low fifth.
I started the high fifth.
Then in the midterm, I went over to the next grade.
And so I was all messed up that way.
So you were half a year behind?
Yeah, half a year behind or half a year ahead, whichever way you want to look at it.
Depends on which school you were looking at.
Why'd you decide to go on to college?
What else?
Well, there's a lot of people who don't go to college.
Well, my folks wanted me to go to college.
and most of the boys I ran with in high school went to college.
And so I came to A&M.
My father had drilled it into me that I should be an engineer, came to A&M, took a year of engineering, and found that was not my forte.
So then the
following year, that was a year wasted, I took agriculture and finished in animal husbandry in 1924.
And that is the class year that I am associated with, identified with, in the Foreign Student Association.
And then after I graduated in animal husbandry, scouting around, there wasn't any jobs.
except working for Purina, so I had had some contact with the people in veterinary school, so I came back and took veterinary medicine, an intensive course.
Of course, I had credit for all the prerequisites, and so it took me, well, I went
Two years, summer and all, took a heavy course.
I had as many as, I think, 36 hours, something like that, one term.
We'd even have night classes.
Really?
Night classes?
Yeah.
Couldn't work it in the schedule, where there were so few of us.
There were about six in your class?
No, it was only four.
Four in your class.
Well, we just shift the things around so that we could have enough people to make a class.
Finally, I finished in 1926.
got my degree in veterinary medicine in 1926.
Can you describe the college campus back in 1920?
Well, the only dormitories were on the military walk, what was called military walk at that time, and
Gine Hall had just been built.
It was at the end of the military, one end of the military walk and Spezo Hall was at the other end.

And essentially everybody except some of what we called the casuals, men who had been in the service or for some reason or other weren't in the Corps, everybody was in the Corps and on the military walk.
And that's where we'd have our formations.
meal formations and all that stuff.
Well, let's go the other way.
The front of the campus was at the railroad tracks where the depot was.
Then there was a gravel street
up to the Military Walk.
Goodwin Hall on the right, YMCA on the left when you got to the end of it.
The President's House was still there.
It burnt several years ago.
It was down there by Speza Hall.
I might mention this.
that they didn't have enough dormitories as the enrollment increased some.
When I was there it finally reached 2,000 and a little more.
And they built some, put up a tent city out there.
Really?
A tent city for the corpsmen?
Yeah.
Four men to a tent that was walled up on
That's really what we call temporary housing.
And they had a bathhouse, a central bathhouse out there, and they called it Hollywood.
Then in back of the, well the, what we used to call the administration building, which
know what they call it now, academic building, the big building with the dome.
That was the center of things academically, and back of that was the chemistry building, which is gone.
Where the library is now.
Yeah, and textual engineering was on one side, on the other side.
Then Francis Hall was
about a block down from the academic building.
Then the end of the campus going towards what is now Highway 6 or Texas Avenue was a horse barn, and it was there about where the administration building is.
There are 2,000 students in
Yeah, they finally made $2,000.
There wasn't that many when I was a freshman, but finally made $2,000.
What did you think of Core Life?
Did it play any role whatsoever in your decision to come to A&M?
Not particularly.
I guess the cost was one of the big things.
A&M was pretty reasonable at that time, and I guess still is, relatively speaking.
But it was very reasonable, and I could go home for $350 and make a term.
Room, board, laundry, and all.
So that was one of the big reasons.
Well, there's a lot of different universities in the state.
and some even closer to San Antonio, like University of Texas.
Why'd you decide over A&M, over those other ones?
Well, I don't know that I can really answer that.
They did, I was urged by some to go to the University of Texas and join a fraternity, but I couldn't afford those things.
We just didn't have the money.
Now, in 1924 you started in School of Veterinary Medicine.
Could you describe the curriculum?
Well, as I say, mine was kind of mixed up because I was so irregular, but
course anatomy, that was one of the big things, anatomy and bacteriology, pathology, well no that came afterwards, embryology.
Dr. Francis taught the anatomy and embryology and
And as I say, I can't give it to you as freshman year, sophomore year, because I was all mixed up.
What about the students?
What about your student colleagues?
Could you tell me about them?
Where they were from, their quality, and what did you think of those people?
Oh, they were good.
Now, well,
Two of them were local boys from around here, and they were all smart enough, and made a pretty good life for themselves afterwards, very successful.
And then we had a few from here and there, I can't remember where they were from.
Dr. Burns was in there with us about that time.
He was from Cuero.
He was just a little bit ahead of me, maybe half a year or something like that, or a year maybe.
But he was in school with me and a man from Texarkana, I believe.
Just here and there, just like all the students are now, just kind of spotted.
Okay, okay.
Another question.
You said that engineering wasn't and animal sciences was your forte.
Why did you decide to continue?
Was it just because there was only a job with Purina and or what are the other reasons for you desiring to continue and going on to become a doctor of veterinarian medicine?
Well I had
contacts with it while I was taking agriculture and that phase of education was much more interesting to me than was just agriculture or the agricultural courses.
So I just kind of drifted in and I had lots of good friends in the veterinary school
There wasn't many in the veterinary school, but we were good friends.
Did they have, and if they did, did they offer you a scholarship or anything like that?
Oh, I didn't have scholarships.
Didn't have scholarships?
No, they didn't have scholarships.
That was to come later.
Okay.
Let's turn to a minute to the instruction.
What did you think of the quality of instruction in the early 1920s?
Oh, it was good.
It was excellent.
Most of the men, in some respects, I guess what they'd consider now were overworked because they taught many courses.
Dr. Francis was one of the, I guess, one of the greatest men I've ever known or had any contact with.
Dr. Marsteller was quite outstanding.
Dr. Leonard over in the hospital.
It seemed Dr. Francis was dean.
Marsteller became dean later.
And well, we had some good men there.
Dr. Price, who taught parasitology and histology.
and bacteriology, public health.
What a teaching load.
He taught all those?
Oh, yeah.
Shoot, all of them.
There wasn't but about six teachers.
I know.
They had to cover the waterfront.
Yeah, yeah.
I've seen how small the staff was by looking at .
There was Blackberg, S.N.
Blackberg.
He taught physiology and toxicology.
I think that's all he taught.
Now, Price taught immunology.
And then Dr. Leonard and Dr. Marsteller down at the hospital, they taught infectious diseases and surgery and obstetrics.
And all those clinical courses you might call, might call them clinical courses.
What was the average number of courses that these gentlemen taught?
I'd say about four.
I guess that'd be about right.
They didn't leave much time for research or anything else, did they?
No, nobody did any research.
Now, Dr. Schmidt did some research, but he didn't teach.
Yeah.
Right.
I wonder what the average teaching load is now.
It's probably two, isn't it?
I can't answer that.
I've been going 15 years from out there and I don't know what the average load is.
I imagine it's about 15 hours, not courses.
I probably teach one or two courses a semester.
It's a trimester now.
It's going back to the semester.
Can you tell me who your favorite professors were?
They all were.
I guess Dr. Francis, Dr. Leonard, Dr. Price.
Now Dr. Dunn, he just taught some special courses like poultry diseases, and I think that's all he gave us.
But you see he was in the in the laboratory producing whole-collar, anti-whole-collar serum and virus, and that was shipped all over the in the state.
So that was
